Examining Police Misconduct - Evidence from Chicago

Sebastian Montenegro

August 5, 2020

I will study data from the Citizens Police Data Project which can be accessed via their website. The datasets can be downloaded at different grouping levels such as police districts, wards, beat, and neighborhoods. The data are presented in comma-separated value files that contain different variables describing the characteristics of the interaction between the police officer and the complaining witness.

You can access the data and code that I used to clean the data files here.

I will start by providing you with a couple of visualizations that are very interesting in order to understand whats going on within the Chicago PD.

We will need the following packages:

devtools::source_url("https://github.com/sebmontenegro/functions/blob/master/preload.R?raw=TRUE")

preload("tidyverse")
preload("readxl")
preload("dplyr")
preload("zoo")
preload("stringr")

The preload function can be accessed via Internet from my GitHub. I created this function to load packages and/or install them on the system when they are not already installed.

Over time

This is how the number of allegations of both overtime for the Chicago PD

allegations %>%
  filter(IncidentDate>=as.Date("1999-01-01")) %>%
  count(Date = factor(IncidentDate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=as.Date(Date),y=n))+
  geom_line(color="skyblue4")+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(x ="", y = "Number of Allegations")

It has a downward trend and has a drop in 2005 and 2016.

Most frequent allegation categories

This next plot presents the most frequent allegation category by finding.

allegations %>%
  filter(Finding!="Unknown") %>%
  count(Category = Category, Finding = Finding) %>%
  filter(n>=15) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Category,-n),y=n,fill=Finding))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(x ="Allegation Category", y = "Number of Allegations")+coord_flip()+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  guides(fill=guide_legend(nrow=2,byrow=TRUE))+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0, hjust=0),legend.position = "bottom")

The most frequent category is Operation/Personnel Violations. However, those allegations may be sustained, not sustained, unfounded, exonerated, or the allegation might be filed with no affidavit.

Most frequent allegation type

The following represents the most frequent allegation type of served in the data.

allegations %>%
  filter(Finding!="Unknown"&Allegation!="Miscellaneous") %>%
  count(Allegation = Allegation, Category = Category) %>%
  filter(n>=230) %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) -> tmp

merge(tmp[,-3],
allegations %>%
  filter(Finding!="Unknown"&Allegation!="Miscellaneous") %>%
  count(Finding = Finding, Allegation = Allegation),
by="Allegation",all.x = T,all.y = F) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(Allegation,levels = tmp$Allegation),y=n,fill=Finding))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")+ #facet_wrap(~District,nrow=4)+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(x ="Allegation Category", y = "Number of Allegations")+coord_flip()+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0, hjust=0),legend.position = "bottom")

Note that Excessive Force with Injury is the most frequent allegation in the records, but none of the allegations is sustained. Also note that sustained allegations disproportionately less frequent.

Final outcome and finding

Now, lets explore final outcome for allegations recorded in the data. The outcome-axis is order in frequency, so that No Action Taken is the most frequent.

allegations %>%
  filter(Outcome!="Unknown"&
           Finding!="Unknown") %>%
  count(Outcome = factor(Outcome),Finding = factor(Finding))%>%
  group_by(Outcome) %>%
  mutate(pct = prop.table(n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(Outcome,level=levels(forcats::fct_infreq(allegations$Outcome))),y=pct,fill=Finding))+
  geom_bar(position = "fill", stat = "identity",color='black',width=0.9) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(pct*100,0),"%")),position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 2)+
  theme_bw() + scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  labs(x ="Outcome", y = "Percentage of Allegations")+ coord_flip()+
  theme(legend.position="bottom") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0, hjust=0))

The vast majority of allegations that end up in some sort of corrective action are Sustained. Note that for those that wind up with No Action Taken, zero percent are Not Sustained.

Interaction under investigation

Race interacion frequency

Now lets dig into the characteristics of the interaction in the data. This following graph shows the race of the officer and the race of the complaining witness.

all %>%
  filter(Outcome!="Unknown"&
           WitnessRace!="No Info"&
           OfficerRace!="Unknown"&
           Finding!="Unknown") %>%
  mutate(Int = paste0(OfficerRace,"-",WitnessRace)) %>%
  count(Int = Int) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Int,-n),y=n))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",fill="skyblue4")+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(x ="Race: Officer-Witness", y = "Number of Allegations")+coord_flip()+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0, hjust=0),legend.position = "bottom")

The most frequent allegation is that involving a White officer and a Black witness.

Race interaction and finding

Lets look into the finding of the investigation and the officer-witness race from the interaction. The race-axis in the following plot is sorted by how frequent it is (just like the plot above).

all %>%
  filter(Outcome!="Unknown"&
           WitnessRace!="No Info"&
           OfficerRace!="Unknown"&
           Finding!="Unknown") %>%
  mutate(Int = paste0(OfficerRace,"-",WitnessRace)) %>%
  count(Int = factor(Int),Finding = factor(Finding))%>%
  group_by(Int) %>%
  mutate(pct = prop.table(n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(Int,level=levels(forcats::fct_infreq(paste0(all$OfficerRace,"-",all$WitnessRace)))),y=pct,fill=Finding))+
  geom_bar(position = "fill", stat = "identity",color='black',width=0.9) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(pct*100,0),"%")),position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 2)+
  theme_bw() + scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  labs(x ="Outcome", y = "Percentage of Allegations")+ coord_flip()+
  theme(legend.position="bottom") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0, hjust=0))

Something striking can be taken from this picture: The percentage of Sustained allegations filed by Black witnesses varies from 2% to 3% and is dramatically lower than that for White witnesses, which varies from 18% to 39%.

Top 10 sustained allegations by race

This is definitely no proof that allegations filed by Black citizens are being neglected or disregarded. But it would be interesting to look into all the allegations for which the investigation found the allegation Sustained.

The following plots show the Top 10 Sustained allegations for Black and White citizens, separately.

Black witnesses

a <- all %>%
  filter(Outcome!="Unknown"&
           WitnessRace=="Black"&
           OfficerRace!="Unknown"&
           Finding=="Sustained") %>%
  count(Allegation = factor(Allegation)) %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  slice_head(n=10) #This is the top 10 for Black citizens

b <- all %>%
  filter(Outcome!="Unknown"&
           WitnessRace=="Black"&
           OfficerRace!="Unknown"&
           Finding=="Sustained") %>%
  mutate(Int = paste0(OfficerRace,"-",WitnessRace)) %>%
  count(WitnessRace = factor(WitnessRace),Int = factor(Int),Allegation = factor(Allegation))

c <- merge(a,b,by="Allegation",all.x = T,all.y = F)


c %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(Allegation,levels = c(as.character(a$Allegation))),y=n.y,fill=Int))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme_bw() + scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  labs(x ="Outcome", y = "Percentage of Allegations",fill="Race Officer-Witness")+ coord_flip()+
  guides(fill=guide_legend(nrow=3,byrow=TRUE))+
  theme(legend.position="bottom") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0, hjust=0))

The most frequent Sustained allegation is Neglect Of Duty and Excessive Force with Injury is fourth.

White witnesses

a <- all %>%
  filter(Outcome!="Unknown"&
           WitnessRace=="White"&
           OfficerRace!="Unknown"&
           Finding=="Sustained") %>%
  count(Allegation = factor(Allegation)) %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  slice_head(n=10) #This is the top 10 for White citizens

b <- all %>%
  filter(Outcome!="Unknown"&
           WitnessRace=="White"&
           OfficerRace!="Unknown"&
           Finding=="Sustained") %>%
  mutate(Int = paste0(OfficerRace,"-",WitnessRace)) %>%
  count(WitnessRace = factor(WitnessRace),Int = factor(Int),Allegation = factor(Allegation))

c <- merge(a,b,by="Allegation",all.x = T,all.y = F)


c %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(Allegation,levels = c(as.character(a$Allegation))),y=n.y,fill=Int))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme_bw() + scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  labs(x ="Outcome", y = "Percentage of Allegations",fill="Race Officer-Witness")+ coord_flip()+
  guides(fill=guide_legend(nrow=3,byrow=TRUE))+
  theme(legend.position="bottom") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, vjust = 0, hjust=0))

The most frequent Sustained allegation is Neglect Of Duty. Although Excessive Force with Injury is not in the Top 10, White witnesses file more allegations that are Sustained.
